cards.name: Spike: Determine effects of longer AWS Resource IDs
cards.description: After December 2016, Amazon AWS will start using longer IDs for various resources. Before then we need to check whether our code can cope (which is likely) and opt in to the new scheme.\\n\\nRepos include:\\n\\n- lpos-chef-repo\\n- spp_aws\\n- spp_release\\n\\nCurrent ID format (for, e.g, EC2 instances) is a resourceID + 8-char string. To be replaced by a resourceID + 17-char string.\\n\\nhttps://aws.amazon.com/ec2/faqs/#longer-ids\\n\\nhttps://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/heads-up-longer-ec2-ebs-resource-ids-coming-in-2016/\\n\\nSpike Outcomes:\\n- understanding of implications\\n- necessary cards raised\\n

[ATLAS] [Opening Hours] Extract list of example input strings
cards.description: Starting with the simplest examples, extract a list of unique "hours" strings from the PoiLocalisation table. Manually translate each into JSON.\\n\\nThe goal is to have one example of each type of input string which we aim to handle within Phase 1, with a corresponding chunk of JSON describing how we want to see those opening hours expressed.\\n\\nSeek verification from @dancorbett for each example input string.\\n\\nNice to have: a list of pathological examples - i.e. input strings that are out of scope for Phase 1.\\n\\nhttps://lonelyplanet.atlassian.net/wiki/display/SPP/Rich-Format+Opening+Hours+specification

cards.name: [ATLAS] [Opening Hours] Spike: investigate 3rd-party parsing tools
cards.description: TIMEBOX: Max 2 days.\\n\\nMaybe someone has invented the wheel before us.\\n\\nIs there a 3rd-party tool that might help us parse the "hours" strings?\\n\\nWe're open to any tech, but bear in mind our constraints:\\n\\n* Server-side only (for Phase 1)\\n* Must be accessible from Rails, though if the response time is fast enough it could be written in any language\\n* Ideally something simple to configure and maintain\\n* Must be able to be customised to our needs.\\n\\nOutcome: agreed choice of 3rd-party tool, or confirmation that there are none available that meet our needs.\\n

cards.name: Extend Atlas performance tests
cards.description: THIS CARD HAS BEEN BROKEN DOWN INTO 3 SMALLER CARDS\\n\\nhttps://trello.com/c/1u17GwcX/1689-extend-atlas-performance-tests-for-places-pane\\nhttps://trello.com/c/EijW8Kbm/1690-extend-atlas-performance-tests-for-cms-pane-narratives\\nhttps://trello.com/c/QN4q5klc/1691-extend-atlas-performance-tests-for-cms-pane-pois\\n\\n\\nORIGINAL CONTENT\\n\\n\\nAlmost all the Atlas performance tests are concerned with managing content in the Manifest pane.\\n\\nWe should probably create some tests to cover interactions in the Place, Narrative and POI panes. Moreover, we should add some tests for the CMS filters\\n\\nSome suggestions:\\n\\n- Add new Places to the Places pane\\n- Use the different content filters to retrieve Places\\n\\n- Add a new Narrative section to the Narratives pane\\n- Edit Narratives in the Narratives pane\\n- Re-file Narratives in the Narratives pane\\n- Delete Narratives from the Narratives pane\\n- Use the different content filters to retrieve Narratives\\n\\n- Add a new POI to the POIs pane\\n- Edit existing POI in the POIs pane\\n- Re-file POIs in the POIs pane\\n\\n- Filter for POI types in the POIs pane using the 5 poi filters\\n- Use the different content filters to retrieve POIs\\n\\n- Search for Narratives and display sub-places\\n- Filter for Narratives with notes
